      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Proponents of tough-on-crime policies often cling to the deterrence argument, believing that severe punishment discourages potential offenders. However, modern criminological research increasingly questions the reliability of this theory in practice, especially considering biases in policing. Many advocates also hold deep-seated beliefs rooted in public safety concerns or political ideologies that prioritize punishment over social rehabilitation. Ultimately, the consensus among many experts is that relying solely on punitive measures is an outdated and insufficient strategy for true public safety.",
